Principal Component Analysis¶

PCA- A unsupervised feature extraction algorithm that aims to maximize the variance along the extracted features

Why maximize variance?

In [1]:
each=200
Ca<-cbind(rnorm(each,mean=5,sd=1.15),rnorm(200,mean=4,sd=1.05))
Cb<-cbind(rnorm(each,mean=14,sd=1.15),rnorm(200,mean=7,sd=1.05))
X<-rbind(Ca,Cb)
cat(" Glimpse of Dataset X: \n")
print(X[1:5,])
cat("\n Dimension of Dataset: \t Samples:",dim(X)[1],"\t Features:",dim(X)[2])
true=c(rep(1,each),rep(2,each))
colvec = c("coral3","darkseagreen3")[true]
pchs= c(22,24)[true]
plot(X,col="black",bg=colvec,pch=pchs,xlab="Feature1",ylab="Feature2",main="Scatter plot of Data")

Variance gives a notion of the structure of the data ¶

PCA Objective Find direction 𝑣1v1 a linear combination of Feature 1 and Feature 2 that maximizes the variance of the projected data

Projected data:

𝑦=𝑋𝑣1(1)(1)y=Xv1

Say 𝑣1=[𝑣11𝑣12]v1=[v11v12], the projected data 𝑦=𝑋𝑣y=Xv implies

𝑦=𝑣11×Feature 1+𝑣11×Feature 2(2)(2)y=v11×Feature 1+v11×Feature 2

𝑦y is a linear combination of Feature 1 and Feature 2.

maximize𝑣𝑎𝑟(𝑦)=1(𝑛−1)𝑦𝑇𝑦=𝑣𝑇1𝑋𝑇𝑋𝑣1(3)(3)maximizevar(y)=1(n−1)yTy=v1TXTXv1

For mean-centered data 𝑋X:

1(𝑛−1)𝑋𝑇𝑋1(n−1)XTX is the Covariance matrix of 𝑋X

maximize𝑣𝑇1𝐶𝑣1subject to𝑣𝑇1𝑣1=1,(4)(4)maximizev1TCv1subject tov1Tv1=1,

where 𝐶=1(𝑛−1)𝑋𝑇𝑋C=1(n−1)XTX and 𝑣1v1 is unit vector as only the direction of maximum variance matters.

Solution for 𝑣1v1 in (4)(4) given by the eigenvector of 𝐶C corresponding largest eigenvalue.

Principal components of 𝑋X : Project 𝑋X on the eigenvectors of its covaraince matrix 𝐶C¶

n=nrow(X)
C=(t(X)%*%X)/(n-1)

In [8]:
y1=X%*%v1
cat("\n First principal component y1= \n ")
cat(" ",y1[1:8],sep="\n")
cat("\n Largest eigenvalue= ",eigC$values[1])
pc1Mat=cbind(y1,rep(0,n))
plot(pc1Mat,col="black",bg=colvec,pch=pchs,xlab="Principal Component 1",ylab="",ylim=c(-1,1),xlim=c(-4, 4),main="First principal component")
text(0,-0.2,paste("variance= ",var(y1)),font=2)
